## LU factorisation

Gaussian elimination  can be interpreted as an LU factorisation. Write a matrix
$A âˆˆ ğ”½^{n Ã— n}$ as follows:
$$
A =  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\ ğ¯ & K \end{bmatrix}
$$
where $Î± = a_{11}$, $ğ¯ = A[2:n, 1]$ and $ğ° = A[1, 2:n]$ (that is, $ğ¯ âˆˆ ğ”½^{n-1}$ is a vector whose entries are the 2nd through last row of the first column of $A$ whilst $ğ° âˆˆ ğ”½^{n-1}$ is a vector containing the 2nd through last column of the first row of $A$). Gaussian elimination consists of taking the first row, dividing by
$Î±$ and subtracting from all other rows. That is equivalent to multiplying by a lower triangular matrix:
$$
\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
-ğ¯/Î± & I \end{bmatrix}}_{L_1^{-1}} A = \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  & K -ğ¯ğ°^âŠ¤ /Î± \end{bmatrix}
$$
where $A_2 := K -ğ¯ğ°^âŠ¤ /Î±$  happens to be a rank-1 perturbation of $K$.
We can write this another way:
$$
A = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
ğ¯/Î± & I \end{bmatrix}}_{L_1}  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  & A_2 \end{bmatrix}
$$
Now assume we continue this process and manage to deduce an LU factorisation $A_2 = LÌƒ UÌƒ$.
Then
$$
A = L_1 \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  & LÌƒ UÌƒ \end{bmatrix}
= \underbrace{L_1 \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
 & LÌƒ \end{bmatrix}}_L  \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  & UÌƒ \end{bmatrix}}_U
$$
Note we can multiply through to find
$$
L = \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
ğ¯/Î± & LÌƒ \end{bmatrix}.
$$
Noting that if $A âˆˆ ğ”½^{1 Ã— 1}$ then it has a trivial LU factorisation we can use the above construction to proceed recursively until we arrive at the trivial case. 


Rather than a recursive definition, we can view the above as an inductive procedure:
$$
\meeq{
A = L_1\begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  & A_2 \end{bmatrix} =  L_1\begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  & L_2 \begin{bmatrix} Î±_2 & ğ°_2^âŠ¤ \\ & A_3 \end{bmatrix} \end{bmatrix} \ccr
=  L_1 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ & L_2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  &  \begin{bmatrix} Î±_2 & ğ°_2^âŠ¤ \\ &  L_3 \begin{bmatrix} Î±_3 & ğ°_3^âŠ¤ \\ & A_4 \end{bmatrix}  \end{bmatrix} \end{bmatrix} \ccr
= \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 
                ğ¯_1/Î±_1 & \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ ğ¯_2/Î±_2 & \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ ğ¯_3/Î±_3 & â‹± \end{bmatrix} \end{bmatrix} \end{bmatrix}}_L  \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  &  \begin{bmatrix} Î±_2 & ğ°_2^âŠ¤ \\ &   \begin{bmatrix} Î±_3 & ğ°_3^âŠ¤ \\ & â‹± \end{bmatrix} \end{bmatrix} \end{bmatrix}}_U.
}
$$
We can see this procedure clearer in the following example.


**Example (LU by-hand)**
Consider the matrix
$$
A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 & 1 \\
                    2 & 4 & 8 \\
                    1 & 4 & 9
                    \end{bmatrix} = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} 1  \\
